title: High-Resolution Study of Isobaric Analog Resonances in 23Na

x4freetext: High-Resolution Study of Isobaric Analog Resonances
in 23Na

x4codes.hlp: Duke University, Durham, NC, United States of America
Duke University, Durham, NC, United States of America

x4freetext: Cryogenic (windowless gas chamber)
target, rare-gas handling system.
Owing to limitations imposed by lack of available
electronic equipment, a maximum of four particles
could be counted in the target chamber at one time.
Therefore, the continuous excitation function for
elastic scattered protons was measured at 90, 120 and
160 degrees and then repeated at the three remaining
angles in the vicinity of resonances. Inelastically,
scattered protons were observed at 90, 120, and 150
degrees simultaneously with elastic protons at 150
degrees. The elastic proton measurement was repeated
to ensure the precise energy alignment between two
excitation functions for elastic and inelastic
protons. Inelastic proton measurements below 2.0 MeV
were strongly hampered by penetration effects, and
could not be observed. Absolute energy calibration
was obtained by measurement of the 7Li(p,n)7Be
threshold.
Most of the elastic scattering data below 2.1
MeV consist of resonances separated by a sufficient
energy to permit their comparison with a single-
level, Breit-Wigner formula. Accordingly, a computer
code (GALAHAD) was written, which includes hard-
sphere phase shifts up to l=4, in which an
approximate linear regression technique was
incorporated to five the best fit, in the least-squares
sense, for the variable parameters E0, G, Gp, and
delta, the width full width at half-maximum (FWHM) of
the resolution function. Above 2.1 MeV, however,
there are few isolated resonances and a multilevel,
multichannel code (MULTI) was written by D.L.Selin
was used to fit the data.
